2.Fit the PCA in the as mtcars.pca with mtcars.subset data with cor = TRUE and scores = TRUE.

library(psych,warn.conflicts = F)
## Warning: package 'psych' was built under R version 4.1.2
mtcars.pca <- principal(mtcars.subset, nfactors = 9, rotate = "none",scores = T,cor = T)

Interpretation: Principal Component Analysis (PCA) is a type of dimensionality reduction algorithm which is used to compress datasets through feature extraction. PCA is used when our data has high number of variables and analyzing all the variables are too tedious. So, instead of analyzing all the variables, the variables are compressed and limited number of variables are created that contains maximum variance of the original data. In the mtcars data, two binary variables are excluded, and 9 principal components are seen using principal method in psych package. The proportion of variance explains that, the first component PC1 explains 63% variance of original data, the second component PC2 explains 23% variance and so on. The standard deviation explains the eigen value of the original data.

#4.Get eigenvalue of the components using standard deviation of mtcars.pca and chose the number of components based on Kaiser’s criteria.

eigen <- mtcars.pca$values
eigen
## [1] 5.65593947 2.08210029 0.50421482 0.26502753 0.18315864 0.12379319 0.10506192
## [8] 0.05851375 0.02219038

According to Kaiser’s criteria, the component having eigen values greater or equal to 1 should be retained. So, observing above eigen values two components PC1 and PC2 can be choosen.

#5.Get scree plot and chose the number of components based on “first bend” of this plot.

var_exp = mtcars.pca$values/sum(mtcars.pca$values)
var_exp
## [1] 0.628437719 0.231344477 0.056023869 0.029447503 0.020350960 0.013754799
## [7] 0.011673547 0.006501528 0.002465598
library(ggplot2,warn.conflicts = F)

qplot(c(1:9),var_exp)+
  geom_line()+
  xlab("Principal Component")+
  ylab("Variance Explained")+
  ggtitle("Scree Plot")+
  ylim(0,1)

Observing the scree plot, we can see the first bend in 2 and applying the first bend rule, 2 components should be chosen in this data.

#6.Write how many components must be retained based on Kaiser’s rule and/or scree plot. According to Kaiser’s rule, components having eigen values greater than or equal to zero should be chosen. According to scree plot, the first bend of the line gives the number of components. In this data, 2 components have eigen values greater than 1 and first bend in the scree plot is in 2, therefore 2 components should be retained.

#16.Plot the cars.mds.2d and compare it with the biplot of mtcars.pca and interpret it carefully.

library(dplyr,warn.conflicts = F)
plot(cars.mds.2d,pch=20)
abline(h=0,v=0,lty=2)
mtcars <- mtcars %>% scale()
text(cars.mds.2d,pos = 4,labels = rownames(mtcars),col = "steelblue")

Interpretation: The above figure shows the plot of multidimensional scaling model of the data in 2 - dimensional state. Multi-dimensional scaling is also the method of dimensionality reduction as like principal component analysis. Multi dimensional scaling compute the classical distance between points. This method visualize the similarity/disimilarity of the data by plotting points.

#17.Fit classical multi-dimensional scaling model with the mtcars.dist in 3-dimensional state as cars.mds.3d

cars.mds.3d <- cmdscale(mtcars.dist, k=3)
plot(cars.mds.3d,pch=20)
abline(h=0,v=0,lty=2)
mtcars <- mtcars %>% scale()
text(cars.mds.3d,pos = 4,labels = rownames(mtcars),col = "steelblue")

# 18.Create a 3-d scatterplot of cars.mds.3d with type = “h”, pch = 20 and lty.hplot = 2 and interpret it carefully.

              type = "h", pch = 20,
              lty.hplot = 2)

Interpretation: The above figure shows the 3d scatter plot of the classical multi-dimensional scaling of mtcars.dist. We can see the distance between the points in 3d. It shows the inter point distance and also the distance from the base.

#20.Write a summary comparing PCA and MDS fits done above for mtcars data. PCA is the dimension reduction method, a very useful method when the study domain has many number of variables. This method is to create datasets from the original data less than the number of original data and yet explain most of the variance. In the above data, mtcars data is used, the two binary variables are eliminated from our analysis and for the remaining 9 variables, suitable number of principal components are chosen that explains most of the variance of the 9 variables. Using scre plot and Kaiser’s criteria, two pricipal components are retained that explains about 86% variance of previous 9 components.

Multidimensional scaling is the method to visualize the similarity or dissimilarity between data using plots. This method used distance and in above code, multidimensional scaling id fitted for 2 state dimension and 3 state dimension.
